frameDefinitions: An Agent or Cause causes an Entity to change, either in its category membership or in terms of the value of an Attribute.
An Entity changes, either in its category membership, its situation, or in terms of the quality of an Attribute.
An Agent changes Tools, from the Old_tool to a New_tool.
An Entity ends up with some Final_quality--a new fact about the Entity.
An Agent adjusts an Instrument to enable it to interact directly with a difficult-to-access Target_location.

This frame models the semantic contribution of negation, in which the profiled content of the Negated_proposition is asserted to contrast incompatibly with a corresponding Factual_situation, which is normally implicit.
frameExamples: Our storylines follows the saga outlined by the Ultima Series, but we have <t>modified</t> it in order to make our writing more cohesive.
As soon as Tiffany kissed the frog, Tiffany <t>turned</t> into a frog.
If this happens one more time, we 're going to <t>switch</t> operating systems.
If you <t>aim</t> your weapons somewhere else , I 'll be more likely to talk .
listRoleDefinitions: The sentient entity that effects a change in the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The category of which the <fen>Entity</fen> is a member before the <fen>Agent</fen> causes a change.
The category that the <fen>Entity</fen> belongs to after it has undergone the change.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> assumes as a result of the change that the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused to undergo.
The value that the <fen>Attribute</fen> has before the change takes place.
A characteristic of the <fen>Entity</fen> for which a value can be assigned or determined by calculation, measurement , or observation.
The abstract or concrete thing or situation that the <fen>Agent</fen> causes to change.
An event that causes a change in the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The time at which the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.
The location where the change of the <fen>Entity</fen> is caused.
The concrete or abstract entity that undergoes a change.
The type of <fen>Entity</fen> that results from the change.
The category that the <fen>Entity</fen> belongs to before it undergoes the change.
The value of the <fen>Attribute</fen> before the change takes place.
The quality of the <fen>Attribute</fen> that results from the change.
A characteristic of the <fen>Entity</fen> for which a quality can be assigned or determined by calculation, measurement, or observation.

The <fen>Initial_value</fen> and <fen>Final_value</fen> taken together as the range through which the <fen>Entity</fen> changes.

The main faith of the church has <t>changed</t> <fex name='val'>between Orthodox, Protestant and Greek Catholic</fex> several times.
The <fen>Entity</fen>'s situation that results from the change.
The situation that the <fen>Entity</fen> began in.
The time at which the <fen>Entity</fen> undergoes the transformation.
The location that the change takes place.
The individual that changes their situation.
The entities controlled by an Agent to achieve some Purpose.
The tool that the <fen>Agent</fen> had been using.
The tool that the <fen>Agent</fen> ends up using.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Agent</fen> acts intentionally.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Agent</fen> makes a change.
The <fen>Entity</fen> which undergoes a change, newly ending up in the <fen>Final_category</fen> or taking on a new <fen>Final_quality</fen>.
A description of a characteristic of the <fen>Entity</fen> after the change.
The category that the <fen>Entity</fen> ends up in after the change.  Typically, this entails taking on a number of new characteristics.
>When the change occurs.
Where the change takes place.
The individual that manipulates the <fen>Instrument</fen> to enable interaction with the <fen>Targeted</fen>.
The <fen>Targeted</fen> is the entity located in an indirectly accessible location relative to the <fen>Agent</fen>.
The object manipulated by the <fen>Agent</fen> in order to interact with the <fen>Targeted</fen>.
The location that the <fen>Agent</fen> wishes to ready the <fen>Instrument</fen> to access.
The <fen>Activity</fen> is undertaken by the <fen>Agent</fen> and is directed towards the <fen>Targeted</fen> or <fen>Target_location</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> takes aim.
The place where the <fen>Agent</fen> aims at the <fen>Targeted</fen>.
The situation which is presented as false overall. The particular focus of negation which contrasts with the <fen>Factual_situation</fen> is not separately marked.

The situation or part of situation that actually pertains, in contradistinction to the profiled situation in the <fen>Negated_proposition</fen> that is asserted not to pertain.  In spoken language and casual written language, but not in normatively edited written texts, the <fen>Factual_situation</fen> may be expressed as an unmarked clause immediately preceding or following the <fen>Negated_proposition</fen>.
